{
  "The countercurrent multiplier system operates in which part of the nephron?": "",
  "Loop of Henle (descending and ascending limbs)": "",
  "Distal convoluted tubule": "",
  "Proximal convoluted tubule": "",
  "Collecting duct only": "",
  "The countercurrent multiplier operates in the loop of Henle, where the opposing flow directions of the descending limb (permeable to water) and ascending limb (pumps out NaCl) work together to establish the medullary osmotic gradient essential for producing concentrated urine.": "",
  "The thick ascending limb actively pumps out NaCl via which transporter?": "",
  "Na+/H+ exchanger": "",
  "SGLT2 (sodium-glucose cotransporter)": "",
  "Na+/K+/2Cl- cotransporter (NKCC2)": "",
  "Aquaporin-2 water channels": "",
  "The thick ascending limb of the loop of Henle uses the Na+/K+/2Cl- cotransporter (NKCC2) on its apical membrane to actively pump NaCl out of the tubular fluid into the medullary interstitium while remaining impermeable to water, which dilutes the tubular fluid and concentrates the medulla.": "",
  "Loop diuretics (e.g., furosemide) block which transporter and in which nephron segment?": "",
  "SGLT2 in the PCT": "",
  "Na+/K+/2Cl- cotransporter in the thick ascending limb of the loop of Henle": "",
  "Aquaporin channels in the collecting duct": "",
  "Na+/K+ ATPase in all nephron segments": "",
  "Loop diuretics such as furosemide (Lasix) specifically inhibit the Na+/K+/2Cl- cotransporter in the thick ascending limb, blocking NaCl reabsorption and disrupting the medullary concentration gradient. This causes massive excretion of sodium, potassium, chloride, and water, making loop diuretics the most potent class of diuretics.": "",
  "ADH acts on which nephron segment to increase water reabsorption?": "",
  "Loop of Henle": "",
  "Collecting duct, inserting aquaporin-2 channels": "",
  "ADH (vasopressin) primarily acts on the principal cells of the collecting duct by binding to V2 receptors, which triggers the insertion of aquaporin-2 water channels into the apical membrane. This allows water to move from the tubular fluid into the hypertonic medullary interstitium, concentrating the urine.": "",
  "Without ADH, urine becomes:": "",
  "Normal in concentration and volume": "",
  "Completely absent (anuria)": "",
  "Very concentrated and low in volume": "",
  "Dilute and high in volume (as seen in diabetes insipidus)": "",
  "Without ADH, the collecting duct remains impermeable to water, so the dilute tubular fluid leaving the ascending limb passes through without water being reabsorbed. This results in large volumes (up to 15-20 L/day) of very dilute urine, as seen in diabetes insipidus.": "",
  "Aldosterone promotes sodium reabsorption and potassium secretion in the:": "",
  "Loop of Henle only": "",
  "Glomerulus": "",
  "Proximal convoluted tubule only": "",
  "DCT and collecting duct principal cells": "",
  "Aldosterone is a mineralocorticoid that acts on principal cells of the late DCT and collecting duct by upregulating epithelial sodium channels (ENaC) and Na+/K+ ATPase pumps, increasing Na+ reabsorption and K+ secretion. Water follows sodium osmotically, increasing blood volume and pressure.": "",
  "Inulin clearance is the gold standard for measuring GFR because inulin is:": "",
  "Freely filtered at the glomerulus and neither reabsorbed nor secreted by the tubules": "",
  "Actively secreted by the tubules but not filtered": "",
  "Completely reabsorbed in the PCT": "",
  "Produced by the kidney itself": "",
  "Inulin is an exogenous polysaccharide that is freely filtered at the glomerulus and is neither reabsorbed nor secreted by the renal tubules. This means its clearance rate exactly equals the GFR, making it the gold standard reference substance for measuring glomerular filtration rate.": "",
  "ANP (atrial natriuretic peptide) is released when:": "",
  "Potassium levels are critically low": "",
  "Blood pressure is dangerously low": "",
  "Atrial walls are stretched due to volume overload": "",
  "ADH levels are maximally elevated": "",
  "ANP is released by atrial cardiomyocytes when the atrial walls are stretched by increased blood volume (volume overload). It acts as a natural counter-regulatory hormone to RAAS by promoting sodium and water excretion, inhibiting renin and aldosterone, and causing vasodilation to reduce blood volume and pressure.": "",
  "PTH affects the kidney by promoting:": "",
  "Calcium excretion and phosphate retention": "",
  "Calcium reabsorption in the DCT and activation of vitamin D (calcitriol)": "",
  "Sodium reabsorption and potassium secretion": "",
  "Bicarbonate excretion and acid retention": "",
  "Parathyroid hormone (PTH) acts on the kidney in three important ways: it increases calcium reabsorption in the distal convoluted tubule, promotes phosphate excretion (phosphaturia), and stimulates the enzyme 1-alpha-hydroxylase to convert 25-hydroxyvitamin D to its active form (1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D/calcitriol), which enhances intestinal calcium absorption.": "",
  "The correct sequence of urine formation processes is:": "",
  "Secretion, filtration, reabsorption, excretion": "",
  "Filtration, reabsorption, secretion, excretion": "",
  "Reabsorption, filtration, excretion, secretion": "",
  "Excretion, filtration, reabsorption, secretion": "",
  "Urine formation follows four sequential processes: (1) glomerular filtration creates the initial filtrate, (2) tubular reabsorption recovers useful substances back into the blood, (3) tubular secretion adds additional waste substances from the blood into the tubular fluid, and (4) excretion eliminates the final urine from the body.": "",
  "What is PAH (para-aminohippuric acid) clearance used to estimate?": "",
  "Cardiac output, measuring the total volume of blood pumped by the heart per minute": "",
  "Glomerular filtration rate, measuring the volume of plasma filtered by the glomeruli per minute": "",
  "Total blood volume, measuring the combined volume of plasma and formed elements in circulation": "",
  "Renal plasma flow (RPF), since PAH is both filtered and secreted so that approximately 90% is cleared in a single pass": "",
  "PAH clearance estimates effective renal plasma flow (ERPF) because PAH is both freely filtered at the glomerulus AND actively secreted by the proximal tubule, so approximately 90% of PAH is removed from plasma in a single pass through the kidney. This makes PAH clearance the best clinical estimate of renal blood flow.": "",
  "What does the term filtration fraction mean?": "",
  "The fraction of renal plasma flow that is filtered at the glomerulus, calculated as GFR/RPF (normally about 20%)": "",
  "The ratio of sodium to water in the final urine": "",
  "The percentage of filtrate that becomes urine": "",
  "The percentage of cardiac output that goes to the kidneys": "",
  "The filtration fraction (FF) is the proportion of renal plasma flow that is actually filtered across the glomerular capillaries, calculated as GFR divided by RPF. Normally about 20% (125 mL/min GFR / 625 mL/min RPF = 0.20), it reflects the efficiency of glomerular filtration relative to renal blood flow.": "",
  "What is the transport maximum (Tm)?": "",
  "The maximum concentration of the medullary interstitium": "",
  "The maximum blood pressure the kidneys can autoregulate": "",
  "The maximum rate at which a substance can be reabsorbed or secreted by the renal tubules when all carrier proteins are saturated": "",
  "The maximum volume of urine the bladder can hold": "",
  "Transport maximum (Tm) is the maximum rate at which a substance can be transported across the tubular epithelium, limited by the number and capacity of carrier proteins. When plasma concentrations exceed the Tm (as with glucose in diabetes), the excess substance cannot be reabsorbed and appears in the urine.": "",
  "What does the term free water clearance mean?": "",
  "A measure of the kidney's ability to excrete or retain water relative to solute, indicating whether the urine is dilute or concentrated": "",
  "The total volume of water filtered by the glomerulus per day": "",
  "The amount of water consumed by the patient per day": "",
  "The rate at which IV fluids are administered during rehydration": "",
  "Free water clearance (CH2O) quantifies the volume of solute-free water the kidneys excrete or retain per unit time. A positive free water clearance indicates dilute urine (excess water excretion), while a negative value indicates concentrated urine (water retention), reflecting the kidney's ability to regulate body fluid osmolality.": "",
  "What is the vasa recta?": "",
  "The venous drainage system of the renal pelvis that collects blood from the medullary interstitium and returns it through the renal vein to the inferior vena cava": "",
  "The afferent and efferent arterioles of the glomerulus that regulate glomerular filtration pressure and rate through changes in their respective vascular tone": "",
  "Specialized peritubular capillaries that run parallel to the loops of Henle in the medulla, functioning as countercurrent exchangers to preserve the medullary osmotic gradient": "",
  "The blood vessels supplying the renal cortex only, including the interlobular arteries and cortical peritubular capillaries that support tubular reabsorption": "",
  "The vasa recta are hairpin-shaped capillaries that descend into the medulla alongside the loops of Henle of juxtamedullary nephrons. They function as countercurrent exchangers, allowing blood to supply the medulla with oxygen and nutrients while preserving the medullary osmotic gradient essential for urine concentration.": "",
  "What does BUN (blood urea nitrogen) measure?": "",
  "The level of ammonia in the urine": "",
  "The amount of creatinine produced by muscle metabolism": "",
  "The blood concentration of uric acid from purine metabolism": "",
  "The nitrogen content of urea in the blood, which rises in renal failure, dehydration, high protein intake, and GI bleeding": "",
  "BUN measures the amount of urea nitrogen in the blood. Urea is a waste product of protein metabolism produced by the liver. BUN rises in renal failure (decreased excretion), dehydration (hemoconcentration), high protein diets, GI bleeding (blood protein digestion), and catabolic states, making it a useful but non-specific marker of kidney function.": "",
  "What is the BUN-to-creatinine ratio used to assess?": "",
  "The adequacy of dialysis treatment, measured by comparing pre- and post-dialysis BUN levels to ensure sufficient clearance of uremic toxins": "",
  "The severity of proteinuria, measured by quantifying the amount of protein excreted in a 24-hour urine collection to assess glomerular barrier integrity": "",
  "Liver function and bile production, assessed by measuring serum bilirubin and hepatic transaminase levels to evaluate hepatocellular integrity and biliary patency": "",
  "Whether azotemia (elevated BUN/creatinine) is prerenal, intrinsic renal, or postrenal in origin": "",
  "The BUN-to-creatinine ratio helps differentiate the cause of kidney dysfunction. A ratio greater than 20:1 suggests prerenal azotemia (dehydration, heart failure) where urea is preferentially reabsorbed. A normal ratio of 10-20:1 with elevated values suggests intrinsic renal disease, and the clinical context helps identify postrenal causes.": "",
  "What does proteinuria indicate?": "",
  "Damage to the glomerular filtration barrier, allowing proteins to leak into the urine": "",
  "Active secretion of protein by the distal tubule": "",
  "Normal kidney function with excess dietary protein": "",
  "Excess protein reabsorption in the proximal convoluted tubule": "",
  "Proteinuria (protein in the urine, especially albuminuria) is a hallmark sign of glomerular damage, as healthy glomeruli prevent large proteins from entering the filtrate. It is an important early marker of diabetic nephropathy, hypertensive kidney disease, and glomerulonephritis, and its presence and degree help guide diagnosis and treatment.": "",
  "What is the normal range for urine specific gravity?": "",
  "2.000-3.000": "",
  "1.000 (same as pure water)": "",
  "1.001-1.035": "",
  "1.100-1.200": "",
  "Normal urine specific gravity ranges from 1.001 to 1.035, reflecting the concentration of dissolved solutes relative to pure water (1.000). A low specific gravity indicates dilute urine (as in diabetes insipidus or excessive fluid intake), while a high specific gravity indicates concentrated urine (as in dehydration or SIADH).": "",
  "What is the tubuloglomerular feedback (TGF) mechanism?": "",
  "A local feedback mechanism where the macula densa senses NaCl concentration in the tubular fluid and adjusts afferent arteriole tone to regulate GFR": "",
  "The process by which the PCT communicates with the loop of Henle": "",
  "A systemic feedback loop involving the RAAS pathway only": "",
  "A mechanism by which the collecting duct signals the pituitary to release ADH": "",
  "Tubuloglomerular feedback is a local autoregulatory mechanism in which the macula densa cells of the JGA sense NaCl concentration in the tubular fluid at the DCT. When NaCl is high (indicating high GFR), the macula densa signals the afferent arteriole to constrict, reducing GFR. When NaCl is low, the arteriole dilates to increase GFR, maintaining stable filtration.": "",
  "A patient with severe congestive heart failure is prescribed furosemide (a loop diuretic) but develops hypokalemia and metabolic alkalosis as side effects. A physiology student is asked to explain the mechanism. Why does blocking the Na+/K+/2Cl- cotransporter lead to potassium loss and alkalosis?": "",
  "Furosemide blocks potassium reabsorption in the PCT specifically": "",
  "Increased sodium delivery to the collecting duct drives more Na+/K+ exchange via aldosterone, increasing potassium secretion, and volume contraction stimulates H+ secretion": "",
  "Furosemide directly destroys potassium ions in the tubular fluid": "",
  "Loop diuretics increase ADH secretion, which directly causes potassium loss": "",
  "By blocking NaCl reabsorption in the thick ascending limb, furosemide increases sodium delivery to the collecting duct. Here, aldosterone-stimulated principal cells reabsorb the excess sodium and secrete more potassium in exchange, causing hypokalemia. The volume contraction also activates RAAS and stimulates H+ secretion in the collecting duct, leading to metabolic alkalosis (contraction alkalosis).": "",
  "During an AP exam, a student is presented with the following scenario: A substance X has a clearance higher than inulin clearance. What can be concluded about how substance X is handled by the kidney?": "",
  "Substance X is filtered AND actively secreted by the tubules, adding more to the urine than filtration alone": "",
  "Substance X is only filtered and not reabsorbed or secreted": "",
  "Substance X is filtered but partially reabsorbed by the tubules": "",
  "Substance X is not filtered at the glomerulus at all": "",
  "Since inulin clearance equals GFR (inulin is freely filtered but neither reabsorbed nor secreted), a substance with clearance greater than inulin must undergo net tubular secretion in addition to filtration. This means the tubules are actively adding the substance from peritubular blood into the tubular fluid, increasing its excretion rate beyond what filtration alone would produce (e.g., PAH, penicillin).": "",
  "A substance Y has a clearance less than inulin clearance but greater than zero. What does this tell you about how substance Y is handled by the nephron?": "",
  "Substance Y is filtered at the glomerulus but partially reabsorbed by the tubules": "",
  "Substance Y is filtered AND secreted": "",
  "Substance Y is completely reabsorbed and none appears in the urine": "",
  "Substance Y is not filtered and is only secreted": "",
  "A clearance less than inulin but greater than zero indicates that the substance is freely filtered at the glomerulus but then partially reabsorbed by the tubular epithelium. This net reabsorption removes some of the substance from the urine, resulting in a lower clearance than would be expected from filtration alone (e.g., urea, sodium).": "",
  "A patient presents with the following arterial blood gas: pH 7.28, pCO2 25 mmHg, HCO3- 12 mEq/L. On an AP exam, you are asked to identify the primary disorder and the compensation. What is your analysis?": "",
  "Respiratory alkalosis with metabolic compensation": "",
  "Metabolic acidosis (low pH, low HCO3-) with respiratory compensation (low pCO2 from hyperventilation)": "",
  "Respiratory acidosis with metabolic compensation": "",
  "Metabolic alkalosis with respiratory compensation": "",
  "The low pH (7.28) confirms acidemia. The low HCO3- (12 mEq/L, normal 22-26) indicates the primary problem is metabolic acidosis (loss of bicarbonate or gain of acid). The low pCO2 (25 mmHg, normal 35-45) represents respiratory compensation through hyperventilation, as the lungs attempt to blow off CO2 to raise the pH toward normal.": "",
  "A physiology professor asks: If you constrict the efferent arteriole of a nephron, what happens to GFR, filtration fraction, and peritubular capillary oncotic pressure? Assume no change in renal plasma flow initially.": "",
  "GFR increases, filtration fraction increases, peritubular capillary oncotic pressure increases": "",
  "GFR decreases, filtration fraction stays the same, peritubular oncotic pressure decreases": "",
  "GFR decreases, filtration fraction decreases, peritubular oncotic pressure decreases": "",
  "GFR stays the same, filtration fraction decreases, peritubular oncotic pressure increases": "",
  "Efferent arteriole constriction increases glomerular hydrostatic pressure (by restricting outflow), which increases GFR. Since more plasma is filtered relative to flow, the filtration fraction (GFR/RPF) increases. The blood leaving the glomerulus is more concentrated (more protein-rich), so the peritubular capillary oncotic pressure increases, which actually enhances proximal tubule reabsorption.": "",
  "A patient with SIADH (syndrome of inappropriate ADH secretion) is retaining excess water. On an AP exam, you are asked to predict the changes in serum sodium, urine osmolality, and urine volume. What would you expect?": "",
  "High serum sodium, dilute urine, high urine volume": "",
  "Low serum sodium (dilutional hyponatremia), concentrated urine (high osmolality), and low urine volume": "",
  "Normal serum sodium, normal urine, normal volume": "",
  "High serum sodium, concentrated urine, high urine volume": "",
  "In SIADH, excess ADH causes inappropriate water reabsorption in the collecting duct, producing inappropriately concentrated urine (high osmolality) with low volume. The retained water dilutes the serum sodium, causing hyponatremia. This is a classic AP exam topic requiring understanding of ADH physiology and its pathological excess.": "",
  "A medical student is studying a patient with Conn's syndrome (primary hyperaldosteronism from an adrenal adenoma). What changes in serum sodium, potassium, blood pressure, and pH would you predict?": "",
  "Low sodium, low potassium, normal blood pressure, and respiratory acidosis": "",
  "Low sodium, high potassium, low blood pressure, acidosis": "",
  "High sodium (mild hypernatremia), low potassium (hypokalemia), hypertension, and metabolic alkalosis": "",
  "Normal sodium, normal potassium, hypotension, and normal pH": "",
  "Excess aldosterone causes increased Na+ reabsorption (mild hypernatremia and water retention leading to hypertension), increased K+ secretion (hypokalemia), and increased H+ secretion in the collecting duct (metabolic alkalosis). This clinical constellation of hypertension, hypokalemia, and metabolic alkalosis is the classic triad of primary hyperaldosteronism.": "",
  "During an AP exam review, a student is asked: Why is plasma creatinine a better clinical marker of GFR than BUN, even though both are elevated in kidney failure?": "",
  "BUN is measured in the urine while creatinine is measured in the blood": "",
  "Creatinine is produced at a constant rate from muscle metabolism and is not significantly affected by diet or hydration, while BUN varies with protein intake, hydration status, and other non-renal factors": "",
  "BUN is always normal in kidney disease, while creatinine always rises": "",
  "Creatinine is only produced when GFR decreases, making it a direct indicator": "",
  "Creatinine is produced at a relatively constant rate from muscle creatine phosphate metabolism and is freely filtered without significant reabsorption, making its plasma concentration inversely proportional to GFR. BUN, while also useful, is influenced by many non-renal factors including dietary protein intake, GI bleeding, dehydration, liver function, and catabolic states, making it less specific for kidney function.": "",
  "A patient receiving lithium therapy for bipolar disorder develops polyuria (excessive urine output) and polydipsia (excessive thirst). Lab values show dilute urine with low osmolality despite elevated serum osmolality. ADH levels are elevated. What type of diabetes insipidus does this represent?": "",
  "Psychogenic polydipsia from excessive water drinking": "",
  "Central diabetes insipidus from inadequate ADH production": "",
  "Nephrogenic diabetes insipidus, where the collecting duct is resistant to ADH despite adequate ADH levels": "",
  "SIADH causing water retention": "",
  "Lithium is a well-known cause of nephrogenic diabetes insipidus, where it impairs the collecting duct's ability to respond to ADH by interfering with aquaporin-2 channel insertion. ADH levels are elevated (the pituitary is appropriately responding to dehydration), but the kidneys cannot concentrate the urine, resulting in large volumes of dilute urine despite high serum osmolality.": "",
  "On an AP exam, a student is presented with the following scenario: A patient has glycosuria with a normal blood glucose of 85 mg/dL. The student must explain this finding. What is the most likely cause?": "",
  "A laboratory error in the glucose measurement": "",
  "Undiagnosed diabetes mellitus causing elevated blood glucose": "",
  "A defect in the proximal tubule glucose transporters (renal glucosuria), resulting in inability to reabsorb glucose despite normal blood levels": "",
  "Excess ADH causing glucose to be concentrated in the urine": "",
  "Glycosuria with normal blood glucose levels indicates a defect in the proximal tubule's glucose reabsorption machinery (renal glucosuria). This can be caused by mutations in the SGLT2 transporter, reducing the transport maximum for glucose so that even normal filtered glucose loads exceed the tubule's diminished reabsorptive capacity. This is distinct from diabetic glucosuria, where the glucose load simply exceeds normal transport capacity.": ""
}